
[1]cousin

   COUSIN, n.

   1. In a general sense, one collaterally related more remotely than a
   brother or sister. But,

   2. Appropriately, the son or daughter of an uncle or aunt; the children
   of brothers and sisters being usually denominated cousins or
   cousin-germans. In the second generation, they are called second
   cousins.

   3. A title given by a king to a nobleman, particularly to those of the
   council.

                             COUSIN, a. Allied.
